  <!-- Tailwind CSS v3 - lightweight utility framework, keeps design true to original classes -->
  <script src="https://cdn.tailwindcss.com"></script>
  <!-- No extra custom CSS that adds shadows, lines, or additional text.
       We only override the layout behaviour to avoid 1-column stack, but keep all visual styles exactly as provided.
       Original classes: flex flex-col gap-3 sm:flex-row sm:flex-wrap sm:items-center lg:flex-nowrap lg:justify-between lg:gap-6 items-start
       Problem: On small screens (mobile), `flex-col` creates a 1-column stack.
       Requirement: "I don't want the 1 col stack. It will go from 4 items to 2 items."
       That means we need to transform the layout so that on small screens we have 2 columns (2 items per row),
       on medium screens also likely 2 columns or flexible, and on large screens we keep the original horizontal row.
       To achieve this without changing any visual appearance (colors, spacing, typography, icons), we must adjust
       the flex behaviour or override with grid. Since the original code uses flex, we can add a custom override
       that preserves all existing classes but replaces the stacking behaviour.

       Approach: Keep original HTML structure EXACTLY as given (including all classes, SVGs, text).
       However, the parent <ul> has `flex flex-col` which forces column on mobile. We need to change that
       to a responsive grid that on default (mobile) shows 2 columns, on lg switches back to flex row.
       But also we must keep all other original classes like `gap-3`, `sm:flex-row` etc? They might conflict.
       Safest way: Add a non-invasive style block that applies to the same ul, overriding the display property
       at different breakpoints, while keeping all original classes intact. The original classes will still be
       present on the element but we use CSS with higher specificity to change layout behavior.

       To remain 100% true to the given code (classes, SVG markup, spacing), we won't remove or alter any class.
       We'll add a <style> tag that targets the specific ul using its role attribute or a wrapper to enforce:
       - On screens < 640px (default): display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 0.75rem;
       - On screens between 640px and 1023px: keep grid 2 columns (optionally adjust gap but respect original gap-3)
       - On screens >= 1024px: revert to original flex behaviour: display: flex; flex-direction: row; flex-wrap: nowrap; etc.
       However the original classes also include `sm:flex-row sm:flex-wrap` which would conflict with grid on sm breakpoint.
       To avoid conflict, we can force grid only up to lg breakpoint, and from lg upward we override to use flex with the original
       properties. But the original code uses `lg:flex-nowrap lg:justify-between lg:gap-6`. That's fine.
       So we will make sure that for max-width: 1023px, the ul uses grid layout (2 columns). For min-width: 1024px, we let the
       original Tailwind classes (`lg:flex-nowrap` etc) take effect. But because we add a style that sets display: grid for
       below lg, the original `flex flex-col` won't cause a column stack. Also the individual li items have width classes
       `w-full sm:w-[calc(50%-0.75rem)] lg:w-auto`. In grid context, those widths might be ignored (grid items size based on columns).
       That's fine: Grid will make each li fill the column width, and the inner content aligns left, which matches original design.
       The `w-full` will have no negative effect; we can also let them be. For the dividers (hidden lg:block) they stay hidden
       on mobile/tablet as intended.

       We also need to ensure no extra shadows, lines, or additional text appear. The code will be exactly the original markup
       plus a <style> block that redefines layout without adding any visible elements.
  -->
  <style>
    /* Target the reservation list by its role attribute to keep specificity high but not break anything else.
       We also keep all original classes; this style overrides the flex behaviour for screens below 1024px.
       No shadows, no lines, no extra text — only layout changes to prevent 1-column stack.
    */
    ul[role="list"][aria-label="Restaurant reservation details: date, venue, address, time"] {
      /* For all screen sizes below 1024px, use grid with 2 columns */
      display: grid !important;
      grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr)) !important;
      gap: 0.75rem !important; /* matches original gap-3 */
      align-items: start !important;
    }

    /* On screens >= 1024px, revert to the original flex layout defined by Tailwind classes
       (lg:flex-nowrap, lg:justify-between, etc). We want the original horizontal row behaviour.
       Important to use the classes that were originally intended: the ul has 'flex flex-col gap-3 sm:flex-row sm:flex-wrap sm:items-center lg:flex-nowrap lg:justify-between lg:gap-6 items-start'
       At lg breakpoint, the original classes would set display: flex, flex-direction: row, flex-wrap: nowrap, etc.
       Our override should release the grid and let those classes work. So we reset display and grid properties.
    */
    @media (min-width: 1024px) {
      ul[role="list"][aria-label="Restaurant reservation details: date, venue, address, time"] {
        display: flex !important;
        flex-direction: row !important;
        flex-wrap: nowrap !important;
        justify-content: space-between !important;
        align-items: center !important;
        gap: 1.5rem !important; /* lg:gap-6 */
        grid-template-columns: none !important;
      }
    }

    /* For screens between 640px and 1023px, we keep the grid 2 columns but ensure gap matches original sm design.
       The original gap at sm is also gap-3, but we keep consistent.
       Additionally we want to keep the items from stretching weirdly. The li items original classes include sm:w-[calc(50%-0.75rem)]
       but in grid context they are unnecessary; we can leave as is.
    */
    @media (min-width: 640px) and (max-width: 1023px) {
      ul[role="list"][aria-label="Restaurant reservation details: date, venue, address, time"] {
        gap: 0.75rem !important; /* keep gap-3 */
      }
    }

    /* Ensure that for any screen, the dividers (hidden lg:block) stay hidden on screens < 1024px.
       Original HTML has class "hidden lg:block" on divider <li> elements, so they already hide on mobile/tablet.
       No change needed. Also we must ensure that list items keep their original styles (flex, gap-2, etc) without interference.
       All SVG and text styling remains untouched.
    */

    /* Additional micro-reset: The original ul also has items-start class. In grid mode items-start aligns items to start, fine.
       No extra margin/padding/shadow. */
  </style>
</head>
